N2  - Introduction: Left Ventricular Assist Devices (LVADs) have emerged as a crucial treatment option for patients with advanced heart failure, either as a bridge to transplant or as a destination therapy. Despite the life-saving potential of LVADs, post-implantation patient management remains challenging, with complications such as infections, device malfunctions, and thrombosis being common. Remote patient monitoring (RPM) systems have shown promising results in improving patient outcomes across various healthcare scenarios. Objective: We aimed to describe the characteristics and outcomes of LVAD patients using remote monitoring system. Method: Patients receiving an LVAD, have been followed by the Satelia® solution, a HF management solution with a remote monitoring system. The system is accessible from any devices, requiring no software installation, no external sensors. This study was conducted in 10 centers in France. Results: This study analyzed a population of 187 patients, predominantly male (81%), with a mean age of 62 years, who underwent LVAD implantation. The majority of the patients had the HM3 type of LVAD (74%) and were treated as a Bridge to transplantation (60%). The main etiology of heart failure in these patients was ischemic in nature (75%) with a mean left ventricular ejection fraction of 23%. Over the course of 17 months (7 days-39 months), patients answered 13,644 questionnaires, resulting in 1,613 red alerts (12%) that were communicated to their cardiologists. The monitoring was primarily discontinued due to death (27%), patient or healthcare professional decision (39%), or other reasons (34%). Additional data regarding the description of the population and the alerts and their resolutions will be presented at the congress. Conclusion: In conclusion, these data may potentially improve patient outcomes by identifying critical alerts in LVAD patients, enabling timely interventions and informing future management strategies in this population.
