N2  - Introduction: The use of venous catheters is often associated with complications occurrence inherent to catheter indwelling in the patient but also to the type of fluid used, which is why patient surveillance becomes crucial, not only for the user but also for health professionals to prevent complications. Since these devices have an extremely specific application, their accessibility can become complex when applied to bedridden people, because of their positioning but also due to the clothing they use, which normally does not have the ideal conditions of design and type of textile (i.e., minimal flexibility, reduced openings). Method: This study comprised an approach based on the evaluation of a textile prototype designed (under the project 4NoPressure) to prevent the occurrence of pressure injuries for the evaluation of an innovative device through a focus group with 19 experts, health professionals with experience in the area of care and how garments may or may not facilitate the performance of health professionals in handling devices on the people themselves or even in accessing and monitoring vascular access. Results: After an analysis carried out by a group of experts, new materials with a specific design promotes thermophysiological control of the skin's microclimate. It was verified that clothing in the form of 2-piece pajamas should be easy to handle with a practical opening system, in the central region or sleeves for easy access to medical devices (i.e., puncture, placement of external fasteners, among others), as well as for their monitoring and avoiding side seams that can promote pressure sore formation. Discussion & Conclusion: In this way, it verified and encouraged the need to establish more multidisciplinary teams aimed at the development of new products not only innovative but also with preventive action to respond to some existing gaps in the market in the health sector.
