N2  - RATIONALE: Auscultation of lung sounds has remained a major challenge to remote patient monitoring, telemedicine including tele-ICU management and post discharge care whether hospitalization resulted from exacerbation or surgery. The Strados Labs Remote Electronic Stethoscope Platform (RESPTM) is the first and only device that offers the clinical staff access to the patient remotely with a wearable device, adhered to the chest wall and designed to capture all lung sounds and transmit them through AWS or SD card retrieval for annotation, interpretation recording and uploading to a clinician accessible portal. METHODS: Volunteers with cardiopulmonary diseases were recruited from the patient population. The placement of the device was based on auscultation of the chest and identification of the optimal site for capturing diffuse lung sounds, including rales, rhonchi, wheezes, cough and intrathoracic sounds not otherwise specified. These studies compared direct auscultation at 4 sites on the chest with adjacent recording using the Littmann3200® stethoscope, followed by removal of 2 RESPTM wearables and finally one wearable, creating a 4:2:1 paradigm. Acoustic recordings were then compared by at least 3 board certified clinicians masked to patient diagnosis and chest wall placement. Some volunteers were asked to cough, swallow, perform a “glottal stop,” count, and breathe deeply at rest and while ambient noise (music) played. Respiratory rate was independently captured using chest wall motion sensing. RESULTS: 10 patients participated in the first study, with no dropouts. The RESPTM provided high fidelity data access substantially similar to the Littmann3200 across a range of patients (COPD, asthma, CHF, chronic cough), with no loss of accuracy or fidelity decreasing from 4 devices to 1. All sounds have been archived. In the second study, the RESPTM was affixed to patients with chronic cough for 8 hours of continuous recording. Together with data from other patients, the RESPTM system was validated for cough counting and provided unique insights into cough architecture and intrathoracic versus extra-thoracic cough origin. CONCLUSION: rigorous testing is required to validate the utility of a remote device to capture and annotate lung sounds. Strados Labs has validated the utility and robustness of the RESPTM in studies designed to stress test the system and to provide the basis for algorithm development and improved nurse: physician collaboration.
