N2  - RATIONALE: The ability to closely track the exercise tolerance of patients with Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension (PAH) in the outpatient setting is typically limited by the resources required for repeat testing. To address this limitation, we developed an Apple Watch based app to enable patients to perform daily six minute walk tests (6MWT's) remotely. To test the app's utility and accuracy we are performing a single-center, feasibility trial enrolling participants with PAH on either stable or augmented PAH therapy (NCT03893500). Methods: All patients receiving care for PAH at Stanford Hospital meeting the study's inclusion and exclusion criteria and deemed good candidates by their PAH provider are approached to participate. Patients who consent are provided with an Apple Watch and instructed on loading the Walk.Talk.Track. App (WTT) and performing a 6MWT using the watch. Concurrent, in-clinic, supervised indoor and outdoor 6MWTs are performed at the baseline and 3-month follow up visits to assess app accuracy. De-identified data collected by the WTT app is transmitted to a secure cloud server, and is analyzed by the study team on a routine basis. Results: To date we have approached 75, and enrolled 29 PAH patients. These patients have 47 yrs median age, 83% female, with a broad range of WHO functional classes (31% I, 55% II, and 14% III). Participants have completed 814 6MWT's since study start, accounting for 210 patient-weeks of exposure (average 3.9 walks/week). The mean difference between WTT app measured distance and the observed gold standard was 8.54±102.2 meters indoor (N=24), and 67.34±68.7 meters for outdoor settings (N=21), respectively. The intraclass correlation coefficient (ICC) of WTT measured walks was 0.77. Technical limitations of the WTT app resulted in 18 walks being omitted from analysis, and an additional 16 walks not recorded (as reported by participants), with an overall device nonperformance rate of 4.2%. Only one, self-limited adverse event related to the study (contact dermatitis) was reported. There have been no reports of dyspnea, angina, or falls related to performing 6MWTs. Conclusion: The WTT app allows for accessible, frequent remote assessment of patient exercise tolerance that is reproducible (ICC 0.77), and can be performed by patients with a wide range of functional class without significant adverse effects. High temporal resolution of exercise tolerance has the potential to guide more rapid clinical decision making, and detect patient decompensation sooner. However, refinement through fusion of different watch sensor data is needed to improve accuracy.
